[36;1mNAME[0m
       io_uring - Asynchronous I/O facility

[36;1mSYNOPSIS[0m
       [36;1m#include <linux/io_uring.h>[0m

[36;1mDESCRIPTION[0m
       [36;1mio_uring  [22;0mis  a Linux‚Äêspecific API for asynchronous I/O.  It allows the
       user to submit one or more I/O requests, which are processed  asynchro‚Äê
       nously  without  blocking  the calling process.  [36;1mio_uring [22;0mgets its name
       from ring buffers which are shared between user space and kernel space.
       This arrangement allows for efficient I/O, while avoiding the  overhead
       of  copying buffers between them, where possible.  This interface makes
       [36;1mio_uring [22;0mdifferent from other UNIX I/O APIs, wherein, rather than  just
       communicate  between  kernel  and  user  space  with system calls, ring
       buffers are used as the main mode of communication.   This  arrangement
       has various performance benefits which are discussed in a separate sec‚Äê
       tion  below.   This man page uses the terms shared buffers, shared ring
       buffers and queues interchangeably.

       The general programming model you need to follow for [36;1mio_uring  [22;0mis  out‚Äê
       lined below

       ‚Ä¢      Set  up  shared buffers with [36;1mio_uring_setup[22;0m(2) and [36;1mmmap[22;0m(2), map‚Äê
              ping into user space shared buffers  for  the  submission  queue
              (SQ)  and the completion queue (CQ).  You place I/O requests you
              want to make on the SQ, while the kernel places the  results  of
              those operations on the CQ.

       ‚Ä¢      For  every  I/O  request  you need to make (like to read a file,
              write a file, accept a socket connection,  etc),  you  create  a
              submission  queue  entry, or SQE, describe the I/O operation you
              need to get done and add it to the tail of the submission  queue
              (SQ).   Each  I/O  operation is, in essence, the equivalent of a
              system call you would have made otherwise, if you were not using
              [36;1mio_uring[22;0m.  For instance, a SQE  with  the  [31;3;1mopcode[24;0m  set  to  [36;1mIOR‚Äê[0m
              [36;1mING_OP_READ  [22;0mwill  request a read operation to be issued that is
              similar to the [36;1mread[22;0m(2) system call. Refer to the opcode documen‚Äê
              tation in [36;1mio_uring_enter[22;0m(2) for all supported opcodes and  their
              properties.   You can add more than one SQE to the queue depend‚Äê
              ing on the number of operations you want to request.

       ‚Ä¢      After you add one or more SQEs, you need  to  call  [36;1mio_uring_en‚Äê[0m
              [36;1mter[22;0m(2)  to  tell the kernel to dequeue your I/O requests off the
              SQ and begin processing them.

       ‚Ä¢      For each SQE you submit, once it is done processing the request,
              the kernel places a completion queue event or CQE at the tail of
              the completion queue or  CQ.   The  kernel  places  exactly  one
              matching  CQE in the CQ for every SQE you submit on the SQ.  Af‚Äê
              ter you retrieve a CQE, minimally, you might  be  interested  in
              checking  the  [31;3;1mres[24;0m field of the CQE structure, which corresponds
              to the return value of the system  call‚Äôs  equivalent,  had  you
              used it directly without using [36;1mio_uring[22;0m.  Given that [36;1mio_uring [22;0mis
              an  async  interface, [31;3;1merrno[24;0m is never used for passing back error
              information. Instead, [31;3;1mres[24;0m will contain what the equivalent  sys‚Äê
              tem  call would have returned in case of success, and in case of
              error [31;3;1mres[24;0m will contain [31;3;1m‚Äêerrno[24;0m.  For example, if the normal  read
              system call would have returned ‚Äê1 and set [31;3;1merrno[24;0m to [36;1mEINVAL[22;0m, then
              [31;3;1mres[24;0m would contain [36;1m‚ÄêEINVAL[22;0m.  If the normal system call would have
              returned a read size of 1024, then [31;3;1mres[24;0m would contain 1024.

       ‚Ä¢      Optionally, [36;1mio_uring_enter[22;0m(2) can also wait for a specified num‚Äê
              ber of requests to be processed by the kernel before it returns.
              If  you  specified  a certain number of completions to wait for,
              the kernel would have placed at least those many number of  CQEs
              on  the CQ, which you can then readily read, right after the re‚Äê
              turn from [36;1mio_uring_enter[22;0m(2).

       ‚Ä¢      It is important to remember that I/O requests submitted  to  the
              kernel  can  complete in any order.  It is not necessary for the
              kernel to process one request after another, in  the  order  you
              placed  them.   Given that the interface is a ring, the requests
              are attempted in order, however that doesn‚Äôt imply any  sort  of
              ordering  on  their execution or completion.  When more than one
              request is in flight, it is not possible to determine which  one
              will  execute  or complete first.  When you dequeue CQEs off the
              CQ, you should always check which submitted  request  it  corre‚Äê
              sponds to.  The most common method for doing so is utilizing the
              [31;3;1muser_data[24;0m field in the request, which is passed back on the com‚Äê
              pletion side.

       ‚Ä¢      Concretely,  for  operations  where strict ordering is required,
              such as for sends and receives on a stream‚Äêoriented TCP  socket,
              it  is  generally unsafe to have more than one outstanding send,
              or more than one outstanding receive (the two directions are in‚Äê
              dependent) on a given socket at a time, as the  kernel  may  re‚Äê
              order  their execution if poll arming or other background kernel
              activities are involved.  However, [36;1mio_uring [22;0mprovides various fa‚Äê
              cilities to enable applications to  efficiently  pipeline  their
              operations  safely.  If  the  requests are submitted in a single
              batch, the application may use [36;1mIOSQE_IO_LINK [22;0mto enforce an  exe‚Äê
              cution  order  in  the  kernel. Otherwise, [36;1mio_uring [22;0mprovides ad‚Äê
              vanced features like [31;3;1mmulti[24;0m [31;3;1mshot[24;0m and send/receive [31;3;1mbundles[24;0m to  al‚Äê
              low  applications  to provide more data in fewer, more efficient
              trips to the kernel. Even if these features are  used,  applica‚Äê
              tions  must  still ensure they do not overlap different sends or
              different receives on a given file.

       Adding to and reading from the queues:

       ‚Ä¢      You add SQEs to the tail of the SQ.  The kernel reads  SQEs  off
              the head of the queue.

       ‚Ä¢      The  kernel  adds CQEs to the tail of the CQ.  You read CQEs off
              the head of the queue.

       It should be noted that depending on the configuration  io_uring‚Äôs  be‚Äê
       havior can deviate from the behavior outlined above, like not posting a
       CQE  for  every  SQE  when setting [36;1mIOSQE_CQE_SKIP_SUCCESS [22;0min the SQE or
       posting multiple CQEs for a single SQE for multi shot operations or re‚Äê
       quiring an [36;1mio_uring_enter[22;0m(2) syscall to make the kernel begin  process‚Äê
       ing newly added SQEs when using submission queue polling.


   [36;1mSubmission queue polling[0m
       One  of  the goals of [36;1mio_uring [22;0mis to provide a means for efficient I/O.
       To this end, [36;1mio_uring [22;0msupports a polling mode that lets you  avoid  the
       call  to [36;1mio_uring_enter[22;0m(2), which you use to inform the kernel that you
       have queued SQEs on to the SQ.  With SQ Polling, [36;1mio_uring [22;0mstarts a ker‚Äê
       nel thread that polls the submission queue for  any  I/O  requests  you
       submit  by  adding SQEs.  With SQ Polling enabled, there is no need for
       you to call [36;1mio_uring_enter[22;0m(2), letting you avoid the overhead of system
       calls.  A designated kernel thread dequeues SQEs off the SQ as you  add
       them and dispatches them for asynchronous processing.

   [36;1mSetting up io_uring[0m
       The  main steps in setting up [36;1mio_uring [22;0mconsist of mapping in the shared
       buffers with [36;1mmmap[22;0m(2) calls.  In the example program  included  in  this
       man  page,  the  function  [36;1mapp_setup_uring[22;0m()  sets  up  [36;1mio_uring [22;0mwith a
       QUEUE_DEPTH deep submission queue.  Pay  attention  to  the  2  [36;1mmmap[22;0m(2)
       calls that set up the shared submission and completion queues.  If your
       kernel is older than version 5.4, three [36;1mmmap(2) [22;0mcalls are required.

   [36;1mSubmitting I/O requests[0m
       The  process of submitting a request consists of describing the I/O op‚Äê
       eration you need to get done using an [36;1mio_uring_sqe [22;0mstructure  instance.
       These  details  describe the equivalent system call and its parameters.
       Because the range of I/O operations Linux supports are very varied  and
       the  [36;1mio_uring_sqe  [22;0mstructure  needs to be able to describe them, it has
       several fields, some packed into unions for space efficiency.  Here  is
       a simplified version of struct [36;1mio_uring_sqe [22;0mwith some of the most often
       used fields:

           struct io_uring_sqe {
                   __u8    opcode;         /* type of operation for this sqe */
                   __s32   fd;             /* file descriptor to do IO on */
                   __u64   off;            /* offset into file */
                   __u64   addr;           /* pointer to buffer or iovecs */
                   __u32   len;            /* buffer size or number of iovecs */
                   __u64   user_data;      /* data to be passed back at completion time */
                   __u8    flags;          /* IOSQE_ flags */
                   ...
           };

       Here is struct [36;1mio_uring_sqe [22;0min full:

           struct io_uring_sqe {
                __u8 opcode;        /* type of operation for this sqe */
                __u8 flags;         /* IOSQE_ flags */
                __u16     ioprio;        /* ioprio for the request */
                __s32     fd;       /* file descriptor to do IO on */
                union {
                     __u64     off; /* offset into file */
                     __u64     addr2;
                     struct {
                          __u32     cmd_op;
                          __u32     __pad1;
                     };
                };
                union {
                     __u64     addr;     /* pointer to buffer or iovecs */
                     __u64     splice_off_in;
                     struct {
                          __u32     level;
                          __u32     optname;
                     };
                };
                __u32     len;      /* buffer size or number of iovecs */
                union {
                     __kernel_rwf_t rw_flags;
                     __u32          fsync_flags;
                     __u16          poll_events;   /* compatibility */
                     __u32          poll32_events; /* word‚Äêreversed for BE */
                     __u32          sync_range_flags;
                     __u32          msg_flags;
                     __u32          timeout_flags;
                     __u32          accept_flags;
                     __u32          cancel_flags;
                     __u32          open_flags;
                     __u32          statx_flags;
                     __u32          fadvise_advice;
                     __u32          splice_flags;
                     __u32          rename_flags;
                     __u32          unlink_flags;
                     __u32          hardlink_flags;
                     __u32          xattr_flags;
                     __u32          msg_ring_flags;
                     __u32          uring_cmd_flags;
                     __u32          waitid_flags;
                     __u32          futex_flags;
                     __u32          install_fd_flags;
                     __u32          nop_flags;
                };
                __u64     user_data;     /* data to be passed back at completion time */
                /* pack this to avoid bogus arm OABI complaints */
                union {
                     /* index into fixed buffers, if used */
                     __u16     buf_index;
                     /* for grouped buffer selection */
                     __u16     buf_group;
                } __attribute__((packed));
                /* personality to use, if used */
                __u16     personality;
                union {
                     __s32     splice_fd_in;
                     __u32     file_index;
                     __u32     optlen;
                     struct {
                          __u16     addr_len;
                          __u16     __pad3[1];
                     };
                };
                union {
                     struct {
                          __u64     addr3;
                          __u64     __pad2[1];
                     };
                     __u64     optval;
                     /*
                      * If the ring is initialized with IORING_SETUP_SQE128, then
                      * this field is used for 80 bytes of arbitrary command data
                      */
