                };
           };

       To  submit an I/O request to [36;1mio_uring[22;0m, you need to acquire a submission
       queue entry (SQE) from the submission queue (SQ), fill it up  with  de‚Äê
       tails  of  the operation you want to submit and call [36;1mio_uring_enter[22;0m(2).
       There are helper functions of the form io_uring_prep_X to enable proper
       setup of the SQE. If you want to avoid calling  [36;1mio_uring_enter[22;0m(2),  you
       have the option of setting up Submission Queue Polling.

       SQEs  are  added to the tail of the submission queue.  The kernel picks
       up SQEs off the head of the SQ.  The general algorithm to get the  next
       available SQE and update the tail is as follows.

           struct io_uring_sqe *sqe;
           unsigned tail, index;
           tail = *sqring‚Äê>tail;
           index = tail & (*sqring‚Äê>ring_mask);
           sqe = &sqring‚Äê>sqes[index];
           /* fill up details about this I/O request */
           describe_io(sqe);
           /* fill the sqe index into the SQ ring array */
           sqring‚Äê>array[index] = index;
           tail++;
           atomic_store_explicit(sqring‚Äê>tail, tail, memory_order_release);

       To  get  the  index  of an entry, the application must mask the current
       tail index with the size mask of the ring.  This holds  true  for  both
       SQs and CQs.  Once the SQE is acquired, the necessary fields are filled
       in,  describing  the  request.   While the CQ ring directly indexes the
       shared array of CQEs, the submission side has an indirection array  be‚Äê
       tween  them.  The submission side ring buffer is an index into this ar‚Äê
       ray, which in turn contains the index into the SQEs.

       The following code snippet demonstrates how a read operation, an equiv‚Äê
       alent of a [36;1mpreadv2[22;0m(2) system call is described by  filling  up  an  SQE
       with the necessary parameters.

           struct iovec iovecs[16];
            ...
           sqe‚Äê>opcode = IORING_OP_READV;
           sqe‚Äê>fd = fd;
           sqe‚Äê>addr = (unsigned long) iovecs;
           sqe‚Äê>len = 16;
           sqe‚Äê>off = offset;
           sqe‚Äê>flags = 0;

       [36;1mMemory ordering[0m
              Modern  compilers and CPUs freely reorder reads and writes with‚Äê
              out affecting the program‚Äôs  outcome  to  optimize  performance.
              Some  aspects  of  this  need  to be kept in mind on SMP systems
              since [36;1mio_uring [22;0minvolves buffers shared between kernel  and  user
              space.   These buffers are both visible and modifiable from ker‚Äê
              nel and user space.  As  heads  and  tails  belonging  to  these
              shared  buffers  are  updated  by kernel and user space, changes
              need to be coherently visible on either  side,  irrespective  of
              whether  a  CPU  switch  took  place  after the kernel‚Äêuser mode
              switch happened.  We use memory barriers  to  enforce  this  co‚Äê
              herency.   Being significantly large subjects on their own, mem‚Äê
              ory barriers are out of scope for further discussion on this man
              page.  For more information on modern memory models  the  reader
              may refer to the Documentation/memory‚Äêbarriers.txt in the kernel
              tree  or to the documentation of the formal C11 or kernel memory
              model.

       [36;1mLetting the kernel know about I/O submissions[0m
              Once you place one or more SQEs on to the SQ, you  need  to  let
              the kernel know that you‚Äôve done so.  You can do this by calling
              the [36;1mio_uring_enter[22;0m(2) system call.  This system call is also ca‚Äê
              pable  of  waiting  for a specified count of events to complete.
              This way, you can be sure to find completion events in the  com‚Äê
              pletion queue without having to poll it for events later.

   [36;1mSQE pointer lifetimes & data stability[0m
       Due to the fixed size of the submission queue entry (SQE) some data you
       provide  in  order to perform a desired operation will be passed in the
       form of a pointer rather than value. In this situation,  you  may  free
       the  memory  backing  the pointer once the succeeding [36;1mio_uring_enter[22;0m(2)
       call has completed; providing it is only required by the operation when
       submitting.

       When [36;1mIORING_SETUP_SQPOLL [22;0mis not enabled, this is  done  when  you  call
       [36;1mio_uring_submit[22;0m(3)  In  The  event  [36;1mIORING_SETUP_SQPOLL [22;0mis enabled, you
       must ensure any provided pointers remain valid until completion.

       However, very early kernels (5.4 and earlier) required state to be
        stable until the completion occurred regardless. Applications can test
       for this
        behavior by inspecting the [36;1mIORING_FEAT_SUBMIT_STABLE [22;0mflag passed  back
       from [36;1mio_uring_queue_init_params[22;0m(3).

       As  an  example,  the  [36;1mIORING_OP_TIMEOUT [22;0moperation takes a pointer to a
       __kernel_timespec struct. This struct is then read by the  kernel  when
       you  submit  the submission queue entries, once submitted, you may free
       the backing memory of the __kernel_timespec as  it  will  not  be  read
       again by the kernel.

       It  should  be noted that this behaviour does not apply to data that is
       read or written while the  operation  is  inflight.  For  example,  the
       pointers  to  a  buffer  used  as  part  of  a  [36;1mIORING_OP_WRITE [22;0mor [36;1mIOR‚Äê[0m
       [36;1mING_OP_READ [22;0moperation must remain valid until completion.

   [36;1mReading completion events[0m
       Similar to the submission queue (SQ), the completion queue  (CQ)  is  a
       shared  buffer  between  the kernel and user space.  Whereas you placed
       submission queue entries on the tail of the SQ and the kernel read  off
       the  head,  when it comes to the CQ, the kernel places completion queue
       events or CQEs on the tail of the CQ and you read off its head.

       Submission is flexible (and thus a bit more complicated) since it needs
       to be able to encode different types of system calls that take  various
       parameters.  Completion, on the other hand is simpler since we‚Äôre look‚Äê
       ing  only  for a return value back from the kernel.  This is easily un‚Äê
       derstood by looking at the completion  queue  event  structure,  struct
       [36;1mio_uring_cqe[22;0m:

           struct io_uring_cqe {
                __u64     user_data;  /* sqe‚Äê>data submission passed back */
                __s32     res;        /* result code for this event */
                __u32     flags;
           };

       Here, [31;3;1muser_data[24;0m is custom data that is passed unchanged from submission
       to  completion.  That is, from SQEs to CQEs.  This field can be used to
       set context,  uniquely  identifying  submissions  that  got  completed.
       Given  that  I/O  requests can complete in any order, this field can be
       used to correlate a submission with a completion.  [31;3;1mres[24;0m  is  the  result
       from  the system call that was performed as part of the submission; its
       return value.

       The [31;3;1mflags[24;0m field carries request‚Äêspecific information. As  of  the  6.12
       kernel, the following flags are defined:


       [36;1mIORING_CQE_F_BUFFER[0m
              If  set, the upper 16 bits of the flags field carries the buffer
              ID that was chosen for this request. The request must have  been
              issued  with  [36;1mIOSQE_BUFFER_SELECT  [22;0mset,  and used with a request
              type that supports buffer selection. Additionally, buffers  must
              have   been  provided  upfront  either  via  the  [36;1mIORING_OP_PRO‚Äê[0m
              [36;1mVIDE_BUFFERS [22;0mor the [36;1mIORING_REGISTER_PBUF_RING [22;0mmethods.

       [36;1mIORING_CQE_F_MORE[0m
              If set, the application should expect more completions from  the
              request.  This  is  used for requests that can generate multiple
              completions, such as multi‚Äêshot requests, receive, or accept.

       [36;1mIORING_CQE_F_SOCK_NONEMPTY[0m
              If set, upon receiving the data from the socket in  the  current
              request,  the  socket  still had data left on completion of this
              request.

       [36;1mIORING_CQE_F_NOTIF[0m
              Set for notification CQEs, as seen with the zero‚Äêcopy networking
              send and receive support.

       [36;1mIORING_CQE_F_BUF_MORE[0m
              If set, the buffer ID set in the completion will get  more  com‚Äê
              pletions. This means that the provided buffer has been partially
              consumed  and  there‚Äôs more buffer space left, and hence the ap‚Äê
              plication should expect more completions with  this  buffer  ID.
              Each  completion  will continue where the previous one left off.
              This can only happen if the provided buffer ring has been  setup
              with  [36;1mIOU_PBUF_RING_INC  [22;0mto allow for incremental / partial con‚Äê
              sumption of buffers.

       [36;1mIORING_CQE_F_SKIP[0m
              If the ring has been configured  with  [36;1mIORING_SETUP_CQE_MIXED  ,[0m
              then CQEs may be posted which has this flag set. This can happen
              if  the  ring  is a single 16b CQE entry away from wrapping, but
              someone needs to post a 32b CQE. As CQEs must be  contiguous  in
              memory, a filler/pad CQE needs to get posted to allow posting of
              the  32b  CQE.  CQEs with this flag set should simply be skipped
              and ignored, they serve no other purpose than to fill a  gap  in
              the CQ ring.

       [36;1mIORING_CQE_F_32[0m
              If  the  ring  has been configured with [36;1mIORING_SETUP_CQE_MIXED ,[0m
              this flag is set when the CQE is of the 32b type. This tells the
              application that there‚Äôs an extra 16b of space in this CQE,  and
              that  to  get  to  the  next CQE the CQ ring must be advanced by
              twice as much as for a normal 16b CQE.

       The general sequence to read completion events off the completion queue
       is as follows:

           unsigned head;
           head = *cqring‚Äê>head;
           if (head != atomic_load_acquire(cqring‚Äê>tail)) {
               struct io_uring_cqe *cqe;
               unsigned index;
               index = head & (cqring‚Äê>mask);
               cqe = &cqring‚Äê>cqes[index];
               /* process completed CQE */
               process_cqe(cqe);
               /* CQE consumption complete */
               head++;
           }
           atomic_store_explicit(cqring‚Äê>head, head, memory_order_release);

       It helps to be reminded that the kernel adds CQEs to the  tail  of  the
       CQ,  while  you need to dequeue them off the head.  To get the index of
       an entry at the head, the application must mask the current head  index
       with  the  size  mask  of  the ring.  Once the CQE has been consumed or
       processed, the head needs to be updated to reflect the  consumption  of
       the  CQE.   Attention  should be paid to the read and write barriers to
       ensure successful read and update of the head.

   [36;1mio_uring performance[0m
       Because of the shared ring  buffers  between  kernel  and  user  space,
       [36;1mio_uring  [22;0mcan  be  a zero‚Äêcopy system.  Copying buffers to and from be‚Äê
       comes necessary when system calls that transfer data between kernel and
       user space are involved.  But since the bulk of  the  communication  in
       [36;1mio_uring  [22;0mis via buffers shared between the kernel and user space, this
       huge performance overhead is completely avoided.

       While system calls may not seem like a significant  overhead,  in  high
       performance  applications,  making  a lot of them will begin to matter.
       While workarounds the operating system has in place to deal with  Spec‚Äê
       tre  and  Meltdown are ideally best done away with, unfortunately, some
       of these workarounds are around the system call interface, making  sys‚Äê
       tem  calls  not  as  cheap as before on affected hardware.  While newer
       hardware should not need these workarounds, hardware with these vulner‚Äê
       abilities can be expected to be in the wild for a long time.  While us‚Äê
       ing synchronous programming interfaces or even when using  asynchronous
       programming  interfaces  under Linux, there is at least one system call
       involved in the submission of each request.  In [36;1mio_uring[22;0m, on the  other
       hand,  you  can batch several requests in one go, simply by queueing up
       multiple SQEs, each describing an I/O operation you  want  and  make  a
